/PGMOTZEY SHABBAT/XX520/XX/PR

/KAHAVDALAH/PR

/ITAt the end of Shabbat, a /MDHavdalah/XX candle is lit. A full cup of wine and spices are near at
hand, and the lights are dimmed./PR

At the end of a festival, and at the start of /MDH/±ol Hamoòed/XX, the candle and spices are omitted
if it is not Saturday night. On a Saturday night when Sunday is a holiday, /MDHavdalah/XX
becomes a section of the Festival Kiddush, page 626./PR

/PR

Elijah the prophet, come speedily to us hailing messianic days./PR

Miriam the prophet, will dance with us at the waters of
redemption./PR

/SCN/XXOTE/XX. Traditionally /ITHavdalah/XX is said after three stars appear in the sky on
Saturday evening, making Shabbat about twenty-five hours long. In fami-
lies that observe this tradition, younger children relish the task of finding
stars./PR

/PR

Some sing "/ITEliyahu Hanavi/XX" at the beginning of /ITHavdalah/XX, and some at the
end. We have put it before /ITHavdalah/XX to set a mood of contemplation. This
order builds toward the mood of jubilance expressed in "/ITHamavdil/XX."/PR

/PR

/ITHavdalah/XX is recited not only on Shabbat but also at the conclusion of Festi-
vals. When Festivals end at times other than Saturday nights, /ITHavdalah/XX
includes only two blessings--the one over wine and /IThamavdil/XX.    /SC/XXD.A.T./XX/PR

/PR

/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. As Shabbat fades, our peopleòs centuries-old yearning for
redemption is voiced through song. When we sing the traditional "Eliyahu
Hanavi," we recall the saving message and leadership of Elijah the
Prophet, harbinger of the messianic age. The contemporary lyrics of
"/ITMiriam Haneviòah/XX" parallel the traditional, offering an inspiring leadership
model. Midrash tells us that Miriam helped to bolster the Israelite
womenòs courage in taking the risk of fleeing Egypt toward freedom. A
prophet in her own right, Miriam led our people in a celebration and dance
after we "took the plunge" to freedom at the Reed Sea (Exodus 15:20-21).
As we strive for םו ןו (repair of the world) and as we pray for the
coming of the messianic age, both Elijah and Miriam are inspiring pro-
phetic figures who model leadership traits that may help to strengthen us
on our journey toward redemption.    /SC/XXL.B./XX/PR

/PR

